<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  You should already notice that every class is best at something, except warrior class.<br>
My proposal if you want a warrior to tank would include new mitigation table for knights and warriors (after all thats what you've done for monks - their own dmg table). Take away parry from warriors and give us block (at a lower skill lvl then monks - this would set us apart from knights in the tanking department).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually, a lot of classes are having problems right now.<br>
<br>
Rangers are third/forth on melee damage and dead last on defense due to how it currently works. Archery gets tossed in our face constantly by people who do not full understand the situation with it. My class should not be balanced solely around a skill that requires Level 60, 45 AA points and a kickass bow just to be viable. Especially when said skill is constantly plagued with line of sight and geometry issues that Verant has stated that they will not fix ever under any circumstance. Oh and kickass bows are few and far between.<br>
Specific Examples of these issues are: Mobs touching walls cannot be hit. Vertical restrictions are too strict. Blades of Grass, rocks, your name/guildtag floating over your head and gnomes routinely block arrows. There is no auto-attack for archery.<br>
<br>
<br>
Things like monks out tanking everyone and knights getting kickass insane ratio two-handers that let them come close to the damage output of rangers and warriors do not help things.<br>
<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------<br>
<br>
What verant really needs to do on the defense side is revamp the whole damage mitigation and avoidance thing. Classes should be grouped by their armour types and each armour type should have its own damage mitigation and avoidance tables. However, Warriors due to their special combat training should have their own table.<br>
<br>
Monks &amp; Beast Lords -<br>
Very High Avoidance and Very Low Mitigation<br>
Defense for this classes should be centered around not getting hit at all. When they do get hit, it should hit them hard and very bad. However their avoidance should not be so good that they are able to tank with it.<br>
<br>
Rangers &amp; Rogues -<br>
Medium Avoidance and Medium Mitigation<br>
Defense for these classes should be better than the two leather classes, and they should be able to absorb hits better due to wearing chain armour. Both damage avoidance and mitigation are in the middle here being neither low or high.<br>
<br>
Paladins and Shadow Knights -<br>
Low Avoidance and High Mitigation<br>
Being plate classes, they should be able to absorb hits better than either the chain or leather classes. However, plate armour is bulky and does not lend for a lot mobility to dodge blows thus they have a lower damage avoidance.<br>
<br>
Warriors -<br>
Medium Avoidance and High Mitigation<br>
While warriors share the same mitigation as the two knights due to plate armour. However while the knights go off to study the mystical arts, warriors go through additional combat training allowing them to move around better in heavy armour.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------<br>
<br>
The offense side needs some revamping as well.<br>
<br>
Rangers should be a solid third, with warriors firmly right behind them.<br>
<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------<br>
<br>
Item Effects<br>
<br>
Another area of muckiness is with item effects. I saw a ranger-only spell as an effect on a CLR/DRU/SHM item for example. Verant needs to stop doing stuff like then and be more original with the item effects. How can they claim that paticular classes are balanced based on their spells, when they are going to duplicate the better spells of that class on items for other classes.<br>
<br>
